 for bestpractices and # Projects Dashboard

## Overview
Create a developer-centric, end-to-end Projects Dashboard for LifeOps that surfaces roadmaps, active tickets, pull requests, releases, CI status, and agent-suggested actions. This dashboard sits at the core of the Project Management Automation workflow, integrating with agent-driven automation (roadmaps, ticketing automation, PR summarization, release notes generation, and CI/CD integrations). It must present a dense, fast-scanning UI optimized for power users, with strong runtime safety for all code paths (null/undefined guards, proper defaults, and validated API responses). A separate Project Detail view exists for a single project, offering backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, agent-run history, and action widgets, while maintaining consistent visual language and architecture.

Project scope includes:
- Frontend: rich, card-based UI with Kanban ticket board, roadmap timeline, PR summaries, CI status, agent-suggested actions, and historical run artifacts.
- Backend: well-structured API surface to fetch and mutate roadmaps, tickets, PRs, releases, CI data, and agent-run actions; run history and audit artifacts are stored with full traceability.
- Automation: integration points for agents to propose actions, summarize PRs, generate release notes, and trigger CI/CD workflows via an orchestration layer with traceability and safety rails.
- User Experience: clear navigation, dense data presentation with scannability, actionable micro-interactions, and robust error handling with user-friendly messages.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Projects Dashboard is the developer-centric hub for LifeOps projects. It consolidates project roadmaps, active tickets, PRs, releases, CI status, and agent-suggested actions into a single command center. It serves as the primary locus for project monitoring, prioritization, and orchestration of automated actions.

Goals:
- Provide a high-density overview that enables rapid discovery, prioritization, and action-taking by developers and operators.
- Surface agent-driven automation prompts and suggested workflows to accelerate delivery while preserving human-in-the-loop control.
- Integrate with the LifeOps Master Dashboard Cronjobs and approvals system to present upcoming scheduled actions, last-run outcomes, and per-run details.

Connected features and integrations:
- Project Management Automation: Roadmaps, ticketing automation, PR summarization, release notes generation, CI/CD integrations via agents.
- Cronjobs system (via Master Dashboard): next run, last run, run history, logs, inter-agent traceability, and approvals queue.
- Audit and run artifacts: every action is explainable, schema-validated, logged, reversible, with an audit trail.

UI elements and visual guidance:
- Roadmap View: interactive timeline with milestones, linked epics, and dependency indicators.
- Ticket Board: Kanban-style lanes (Backlog, In Progress, In Review, Done) with agent-suggested prioritization and quick actions.
- PRs & Code Review: list of open PRs with agent-generated summaries, suggested reviewers, and quick review actions.
- Releases & CI Status: pipeline run cards with outcome highlights, time-to-deploy estimates, and actionable remediation steps.
- Agent Suggestions: a dedicated panel/cards showing next steps, automation recipes, and potential optimizations.
- Top navigation and breadcrumbs tailored for quick context switching across Projects and Project Detail.
- Visual guidance uses the provided dark UI theme with high-contrast typography and sparse but meaningful accent usage.

Connected Page: Project Detail
- Single project view with backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, agent-run history, and action widgets. Shares the same visual language and data interaction patterns for consistency.

## Components to Build
- Projects Dashboard Shell
  - Layout: persistent left navigation rail, top header, content grid with responsive breakpoints
  - State: currently selected project, tab/section state, global filters (team, status, priority), and user permissions
- RoadmapTimelineCard
  - Interactive timeline with milestones, epics, and dependencies
  - Drag-to-resize or click-to-view details (read-only in some modes)
- TicketKanbanBoard
  - Columns: Backlog, In Progress, In Review, Done
  - Drag-and-drop support (with optimistic updates) and agent-prioritization hints
  - Card components with title, assignee, priority, status, estimate, and agent-suggested actions
- PRSummariesPanel
  - List of open PRs with agent-generated summaries, suggested reviewers, and quick actions (approve/review/request changes)
- CIReleasePanel
  - Pipeline run cards with status, duration, and failure highlights
  - Quick toggles to re-run or view logs
- AgentSuggestionsPanel
  - Cards for next steps, automation recipes, and tactical actions
  - Ability to accept/apply suggestions or convert to automation rules
- ApprovalsQueue
  - List/table of scheduled actions requiring human approval
  - Filters by project, agent, due date, risk, and spend constraints
- CronjobOverview
  - Next run, last run outcome, per-run details, and quick drill-down into run artifacts
- ProjectDetailLinkCard
  - Summary stats and quick actions to navigate from dashboard to detail
- DataVizPanel
  - Lightweight charts or sparklines for CI trends, velocity, burn-downs, and release cadence
- AuditTrailPanel
  - Run artifacts, inter-agent messages, diffs, logs, and reversibility controls
- API Integration Layer (Frontend)
  - Fetchers and hooks with robust null-safety, array guards, and type validation
  - Centralized error handling and retry strategies

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React (TypeScript) with a modular component architecture
- State Management: useState/useEffect for local UI state; optional useReducer or context for cross-component state; consider React Query or SWR for data fetching with caching and stale-while-revalidate patterns
- Typing: strict TypeScript types for all data models (Project, Roadmap, Ticket, PR, Release, CI, Run, AgentSuggestion, Cronjob, Approval)
- Accessibility: ensure keyboard navigation, screen reader labels, and proper ARIA attributes
- Performance: virtualization for long lists (e.g., tickets, PRs), lazy loading of charts, and memoization where applicable
- Runtime safety: enforce the non-negotiable safety rules
  - Use data ?? [] for Supabase results
  - Guard array operations with Array.isArray checks
  - Initialize useState with array types, e.g., useState<T[]>([])
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- UI Interactions:
  - Drag-and-drop support for Kanban (with safe fallbacks if drag isn’t available)
  - Click-to-expand/detail views in timeline and cards
  - Real-time-ish feel via optimistic updates with clear rollback on error
- Theming and styling:
  - Implement the provided color palette and typography guidelines
  - Create reusable UI primitives: Card, Button, Input, Toggle, Badge, Chip, Avatar, Icon
  - Use gradients and shadows as specified for depth
- Data validation and error states:
  - Show user-friendly empty states when no data exists
  - Graceful error messages with retry options
- API surface integration (client):
  - Endpoints to fetch: projects, roadmaps, tickets, PRs, releases, CI status, agent suggestions, run history, approvals
  - Endpoints to mutate: update ticket status, add comments, trigger actions, approve/deny actions, create cronjobs
  - Ensure consistent data shapes in frontend by validating shape with runtime checks

### Backend
- Data Models (persistent storage, e.g., Postgres or Supabase-like layer):
  - Project (id, name, description, owner, team, createdAt, updatedAt)
  - Roadmap (id, projectId, title, description, startDate, endDate, status, epics: Epic[]; list of milestones)
  - Epic (id, roadmapId, title, description, startDate, endDate, status, dependencies)
  - Ticket (id, projectId, title, description, status, priority, assigneeId, createdAt, updatedAt, dueDate, source)
  - PR (id, projectId, title, description, status, authorId, reviewers, summary, createdAt, updatedAt)
  - Release (id, projectId, version, notes, plannedDate, releasedDate, status)
  - CIJob (id, projectId, name, status, startedAt, finishedAt, logs, artifacts)
  - AgentSuggestion (id, projectId, type, content, createdAt, relatedItemId, status)
  - RunArtifact (id, runId, type, payload, timestamp)
  - Cronjob (id, name, enabled, schedule, timezone, triggerType, target, inputPayload, permissions, constraints, safetyRails, retryPolicy, outputs)
  - Approval (id, cronjobId, status, reviewerId, comments, createdAt, reviewedAt)
- APIs (REST or GraphQL) to support:
  - Read/write for all data models listed above
  - Pagination, filtering, and sorting where appropriate
  - Validation: server-side schema validation; return well-structured error objects
  - Audit/logging: traceability for actions, agent handoffs, and run artifacts
- Cronjobs subsystem:
  - Schedule parsing and execution engine
  - Timezone-aware scheduling
  - Input payload templating and variable substitution
  - Safety rails: prompts requiring confirmation, bounded auto-pilot rules
  - Output collection: run history, logs, inter-agent traces, diffs, artifacts, errors
- Security:
  - Authentication and authorization (RBAC) to guard access to projects and actions
  - Permissions per action: view, edit, automate, approve
  - Input validation and rate limiting
- Validation & reliability:
  - Defensive checks for nulls and missing fields
  - Use of IDs and UUIDs; referential integrity
  - Idempotent endpoints for actions that can be retried

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Frontend fetches from backend endpoints; data is normalized on the server and validated on both ends
  - Cronjobs generate agent actions and push outputs to RunArtifact and AgentSuggestion records
  - Approvals queue feeds into automation pipelines or manual triggers
  - Agent suggestions can be accepted to auto-create automation rules or manual tasks
- Inter-agent communication:
  - All agent-to-agent messages must be traceable, with an identifier, timestamp, and context
  - Logs and artifacts are stored and retrievable for audit
- Error handling:
  - Centralized error formatter; user-friendly messages in UI
  - Re-try logic and dead-letter handling for failed cron jobs

## User Experience Flow
- Access and Overview:
  - User lands on Projects Dashboard; selects a project from the left rail
  - Dashboard loads roadmaps, tickets, PRs, CI status, releases, and agent suggestions
- Roadmap Exploration:
  - User reviews milestones; clicks a milestone to view epic details and linked tickets
  - Agent suggestions for roadmap actions appear as optional next steps
- Ticket Management:
  - User sees Kanban lanes; drags tickets between lanes, assigns, or prioritizes with agent guidance
  - Ticket cards show title, priority, assignee, and quick actions (comment, assign, tag)
- PR & Code Review:
  - PR panel shows open PRs; click for summary, suggested reviewers, and actions (approve, request changes)
- CI & Release:
  - CI status cards show latest runs; click to view logs and errors
  - Release panel lists upcoming/ongoing releases, notes, and statuses
- Agent Suggestions & Automation:
  - Agent suggestions appear as cards; user can apply to automation, or convert into cronjobs
  - Approvals queue surfaces scheduled actions requiring review; user approves or defers
- Project Detail:
  - User navigates to a single project detail page for deeper inspection: backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, agent-run history, and action widgets
  - All actions are reversible; an audit trail is accessible for every action

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: see Backend section for schema outlines
- API Endpoints:
  - GET /projects
  - GET /projects/{id}
  - GET /projects/{id}/roadmaps
  - GET /projects/{id}/tickets
  - GET /projects/{id}/prs
  - GET /projects/{id}/releases
  - GET /projects/{id}/ci
  - GET /projects/{id}/agentsuggestions
  - GET /projects/{id}/runs
  - POST /tickets/{id}/move
  - POST /tickets/{id}/comment
  - POST /prs/{id}/review
  - POST /cronjobs
  - POST /approvals
  - etc. All endpoints must defensively handle nulls and validate shapes
- Security:
  - JWT/OAuth-based authentication
  - RBAC with roles: admin, maintainer, developer, viewer
  - Compliance with data access restrictions per project
- Validation:
  - Server-side validation for all inputs
  - Client-side guards for arrays: (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks
- Validation Rules:
  - IDs must be valid UUIDs
  - Dates ISO 8601
  - Strings trimmed and sanitized
  - Numeric fields within expected ranges
  - Optional fields gracefully handled with defaults

## Acceptance Criteria
- User Scenarios:
  - The dashboard loads within 2 seconds for a project with up to 1,000 tickets and 100 PRs; all sections render without runtime errors
  - All array data paths are guarded: no map/filter/reduce on potentially null values
  - All API responses are validated and defaulted to empty arrays when data is missing
  - Drag-and-drop Kanban works with optimistic updates and proper rollback on error
  - Agent suggestions can be applied to create automation rules or initiate cronjobs
  - Approvals queue correctly surfaces actions requiring review with accurate statuses
  - Cronjob dashboard shows next run time, last outcome, and per-run details
  - Project Detail view mirrors dashboard data with additional backlog and agent-run history
- Accessibility and keyboard navigation pass
- Security: unauthorized users cannot access project data
- Visual fidelity: UI adheres to color, typography, spacing, and component guidelines with no broken layouts

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Dark UI with high contrast headings and muted metadata
- Dense information architecture with clear visual hierarchy
- Consistent card-based surfaces with depth and subtle borders
- Left navigation rail and top controls for efficient multi-project management
- Minimal but meaningful accent usage to indicate actions, alerts, and status
- Data viz uses limited color palette for clarity and legibility

## Visual Style

Color Palette (as given):
- Primary background: #0B0B0C
- Secondary surface: #151718
- Tertiary surface / panel outline: #1F1F20
- Primary text: #FFFFFF
- Secondary text: #9DA3A6
- Subtle text: #56595B
